{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 11:41:48.049979", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and Topology\n- Fabric: 1 super-spine (AS65000), 2 spines (AS65100/65101), 2 leaves (AS65200/65201), 2 hosts.\n- Host subnets:\n  - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24 via leaf_router_0_0 (10.0.0.1)\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24 via leaf_router_0_1 (10.0.1.1)\n- All inter-router links are /31 in 172.16.0.0/16.\n\nHealth Summary\n- Control-plane (BGP): Healthy across the fabric. All EBGP sessions are established and both leaf/pod prefixes are learned at spines and super-spine.\n  - leaf_router_0_0 (AS65200): peers up to both spines, advertises 10.0.0.0/24, learns 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS65201): peers up to both spines, advertises 10.0.1.0/24, learns 10.0.0.0/24.\n  - spines and super-spine have both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 installed via EBGP.\n- Data-plane: End-to-end host reachability is broken between subnets. Local connectivity is asymmetric:\n  - pc_0_1 ↔ leaf_router_0_1: OK (L3 ping to gateway and leaf loopback uplink OK).\n  - pc_0_0 ↔ leaf_router_0_0: abnormal behavior observed from router side; pc_0_0 ping commands intermittently time out from the test harness.\n\nDetected Anomalies and Evidence\n1) Blackhole route on leaf_router_0_0 for its own connected network\n- leaf_router_0_0 Linux routing table:\n  - blackhole 10.0.0.0/24\n  - 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 dev eth0 proto bgp (learned correctly)\n- FRR on leaf_router_0_0 shows both:\n  - K * 10.0.0.0/24 unreachable (blackhole)\n  - C>* 10.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, eth2\n- ip addr confirms eth2 is 10.0.0.1/24 (should normally produce a connected route 10.0.0.0/24 dev eth2). The blackhole route is overriding intended local delivery.\n\n2) Leaf 0_0 cannot IP-reach its directly connected host, while L2 works\n- On leaf_router_0_0:\n  - arping to 10.0.0.2 returns replies with correct MAC (L2 connectivity is good).\n  - ping -c 2 10.0.0.2 fails immediately (“connect: Invalid argument”) consistent with a kernel blackhole route preventing IP forwarding to that subnet.\n- On leaf_router_0_1:\n  - ping to its host 10.0.1.2 succeeds, no blackhole present. This establishes the asymmetry is only on leaf_router_0_0.\n\n3) Host-to-host traffic fails\n- pc_0_0 ↔ pc_0_1: ping attempts time out.\n- Reasoning with routes:\n  - pc_0_0 → pc_0_1: forward path from leaf_router_0_0 to spines OK (BGP route to 10.0.1.0/24 exists).\n  - Return path pc_0_1 → pc_0_0: traffic reaches leaf_router_0_0, but packets to 10.0.0.2 match the blackhole 10.0.0.0/24 and are dropped. This explains end-to-end failure.\n\n4) Additional symptomatic observation\n- pc_0_0 → 172.16.0.5 (leaf_router_0_0 uplink address) ping timed out; the return path to 10.0.0.2 would also hit the blackhole route on the leaf, causing failure.\n\nLocalization of Fault\n- Fault is localized to leaf_router_0_0’s L3 FIB (Linux kernel routing table). All other devices (leaf_router_0_1, both spines, super_spine) show normal BGP and correct routes without blackholes to their local subnets.\n\nLikely Root Cause\n- A misconfigured/null (blackhole) route for 10.0.0.0/24 present in the Linux kernel on leaf_router_0_0 is overriding the expected connected route via eth2. This results in the leaf discarding traffic destined to its own directly connected host subnet, breaking both local host reachability (from the router’s IP perspective) and any return traffic to 10.0.0.0/24 from elsewhere in the fabric.\n- FRR configuration on leaf_router_0_0 appears normal (advertising 10.0.0.0/24, EBGP sessions up). The blackhole route does not appear in FRR config and is likely a Linux kernel/static route artifact unrelated to BGP policies.\n\nImpact\n- All traffic destined to 10.0.0.0/24 is dropped at leaf_router_0_0, rendering pc_0_0 unreachable from the rest of the network and causing inter-host connectivity (pc_0_0 ↔ pc_0_1) to fail. Local L2 remains healthy but IP forwarding to that subnet is suppressed by the blackhole route.", "generati